# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fluentd
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fluentd/architecture] Fluentd tries to structure data as JSON as much as possible: this allows Fluentd to **unify** all facets of processing log data: collecting, filtering, buffering, and outputting logs across **multiple sources and destinations** (Unified Logging Layer).
[src:fluentd/architecture] The downstream data processing is much easier with JSON, since it has enough structure to be accessible while retaining flexible schemas.
[src:fluentd/architecture] Fluentd has a flexible plugin system that allows the community to extend its functionality.
[src:fluentd/architecture] Our 500+ community-contributed plugins connect dozens of data sources and data outputs.
[src:fluentd/architecture] By leveraging the plugins, you can start making better use of your logs right away.
[src:fluentd/architecture] Fluentd is written in a combination of C language and Ruby, and requires very little system resource.
[src:fluentd/architecture] The vanilla instance runs on 30-40MB of memory and can process 13,000 events/second/core.
[src:fluentd/architecture] If you have tighter memory requirements (-450kb), check out Fluent Bit, the lightweight forwarder for Fluentd.
[src:fluentd/architecture] Fluentd supports memory- and file-based buffering to prevent inter-node data loss.
[src:fluentd/architecture] Fluentd also supports robust failover and can be set up for high availability.
[src:fluentd/architecture] 2,000+ data-driven companies rely on Fluentd to differentiate their products and services through a better use and understanding of their log data.
[src:fluentd/architecture] Fluentd was conceived by Sadayuki "Sada" Furuhashi in 2011.
[src:fluentd/architecture] Sada is a co-founder of Treasure Data, Inc., a primary sponsor of the Fluentd project.
[src:fluentd/architecture] Since being open-sourced in October 2011, the Fluentd project has grown dramatically: dozens of contributors, hundreds of community-contributed plugins, thousands of users, and trillions of events collected, filtered and stored.
[src:fluentd/architecture] Fluentd was accepted to Cloud Native Computing Foundation on November 8, 2016 and is at the Graduated project maturity level on 2019.
[src:fluentd/architecture] And its development is maintained with the community.
[src:fluentd/architecture] You need commercial-grade support from Fluentd committers and experts?
[src:fluentd/architecture] Fluentd is a hosted project under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF).
[src:fluentd/architecture] All components are available under the Apache 2 License.
[src:fluentd/architecture] The Linux Foundation has registered trademarks and uses trademarks.
[src:fluentd/architecture] For a list of trademarks of The Linux Foundation, please see our Trademark Usage page.
[src:fluentd/docs-fluentd-org] is an open-source data collector for a unified logging layer.
[src:fluentd/docs-fluentd-org] Fluentd allows you to unify data collection and consumption for better use and understanding of data.
[src:fluentd/fluentd] Fluentd was positioned for "big data," semi- or un-structured data sets.
[src:fluentd/fluentd] It analyzes event logs, application logs, and clickstreams.
[src:fluentd/fluentd] According to Suonsyrjä and Mikkonen, the "core idea of Fluentd is to be the unifying layer between different types of log inputs and outputs.", Fluentd is available on Linux, macOS, and Windows.
[src:fluentd/fluentd] Fluentd was created by Sadayuki Furuhashi as a project of the Mountain View-based firm Treasure Data.
[src:fluentd/fluentd] Written primarily in Ruby, its source code was released as open-source software in October 2011.
[src:fluentd/fluentd] The company announced $5 million of funding in 2013.
[src:fluentd/fluentd] Treasure Data was then sold to Arm Ltd. in 2018.
[src:fluentd/fluentd] Fluentd was one of the data collection tools recommended by Amazon Web Services in 2013, when it was said to be similar to Apache Flume or Scribe.
[src:fluentd/fluentd] Google Cloud Platform's BigQuery recommends Fluentd as the default real-time data-ingestion tool, and uses Google's customized version of Fluentd, called google-fluent, as a default logging agent.
[src:fluentd/fluentd] Fluent Bit is a log processor and log forwarder that is being developed as a CNCF sub-project under the umbrella of Fluent project.
[src:fluentd/fluentd] Fluentd is written in C and Ruby and consumes at least 60 megabytes of memory.
[src:fluentd/fluentd] Fluent Bit is written only in C, with no dependencies, and consumes approximately one megabyte of memory, making it easier to run under embedded Linux and in containers.
[src:fluentd/log-management] The primary drivers for log management implementations are concerns about security, system and network operations (such as system or network administration) and regulatory compliance.
[src:fluentd/log-management] Logs are generated by nearly every computing device, and can often be directed to different locations both on a local file system or remote system.
[src:fluentd/log-management] Users and potential users of log management may purchase complete commercial tools or build their own log-management and intelligence tools, assembling the functionality from various open-source components, or acquire (sub-)systems from commercial vendors.
[src:fluentd/log-management] Log management is a complicated process and organizations often make mistakes while approaching it.
[src:fluentd/log-management] Logging can produce technical information usable for the maintenance of applications or websites.
[src:fluentd/log-management] Organizations can use different log-analyzers for analyzing the logs of devices in the security perimeter, typically aiming to identify patterns of attack on the perimeter infrastructure of the organization.
[src:fluentd/log-management] Organizations may mandate logging to identify the access and usage of confidential data within the security perimeter.
[src:fluentd/log-management] A log analyzer can also track and monitor the performance and availability of systems at the level of the enterprise, especially of those information assets whose availability organizations regard as vital.
[src:fluentd/log-management] Organizations may integrate the logs of various business applications into an enterprise log manager for a better value proposition.
[src:fluentd/syslog] In computing, **syslog** (/ˈsɪslɒɡ/) is a standard for message logging.
[src:fluentd/syslog] It allows separation of the software that generates messages, the system that stores them, and the software that reports and analyzes them.
[src:fluentd/syslog] Each message is labeled with a facility code, indicating the type of system generating the message, and is assigned a severity level.
[src:fluentd/syslog] Computer system designers may use syslog for system management and security auditing as well as general informational, analysis, and debugging messages.
[src:fluentd/syslog] A wide variety of devices, such as printers, routers, and message receivers across many platforms, use the syslog standard.
[src:fluentd/syslog] This permits the consolidation of logging data from different types of systems in a central repository.
[src:fluentd/syslog] Implementations of syslog exist for many operating systems.
[src:fluentd/syslog] When operating over a network, syslog uses a client-server architecture where a **syslog server** listens for and logs messages coming from clients.
[src:fluentd/syslog] Syslog was developed in the 1980s by Eric Allman as part of the Sendmail project.
[src:fluentd/syslog] It was readily adopted by other applications and has since become the standard logging solution on Unix-like systems.
[src:fluentd/syslog] A variety of implementations also exist on other operating systems and it is commonly found in network devices, such as routers.
[src:fluentd/syslog] Syslog originally functioned as a de facto standard, without any authoritative published specification, and many implementations existed, some of which were incompatible.
[src:fluentd/syslog] The Internet Engineering Task Force documented the status quo in RFC 3164 in August 2001.
[src:fluentd/syslog] It was standardized by RFC 5424 in March 2009.
[src:fluentd/syslog] Various companies have attempted to claim patents for specific aspects of syslog implementations.
[src:fluentd/syslog] This has had little effect on the use and standardization of the protocol.
[src:fluentd/syslog] The information provided by the originator of a syslog message includes the facility code and the severity level.
[src:fluentd/syslog] The syslog software adds information to the information header before passing the entry to the syslog receiver.
[src:fluentd/syslog] Such components include an originator process ID, a timestamp, and the hostname or IP address of the device.
[src:fluentd/syslog] A facility code is used to specify the type of system that is logging the message.
[src:fluentd/syslog] Messages with different facilities may be handled differently.
[src:fluentd/syslog] The mapping between facility code and keyword is not uniform in different operating systems and syslog implementations.
[src:fluentd/syslog] The meaning of severity levels other than *Emergency* and *Debug* are relative to the application.
[src:fluentd/syslog] For example, if the purpose of the system is to process transactions to update customer account balance information, an error in the final step should be assigned *Alert* level.
[src:fluentd/syslog] However, an error occurring in an attempt to display the ZIP code of the customer may be assigned *Error* or even *Warning* level.
[src:fluentd/syslog] The server process that handles display of messages usually includes all lower (more severe) levels when the display of less severe levels is requested.
[src:fluentd/syslog] That is, if messages are separated by individual severity, a *Warning* level entry will also be included when filtering for *Notice*, *Info* and *Debug* messages.
[src:fluentd/syslog] In RFC 3164, the message component (known as MSG) was specified as having these fields: *TAG*, which should be the name of the program or process that generated the message, and *CONTENT* which contains the details of the message.
[src:fluentd/syslog] Described in RFC 5424, "MSG is what was called CONTENT in RFC 3164.
[src:fluentd/syslog] The TAG is now part of the header, but not as a single field.
[src:fluentd/syslog] The TAG has been split into APP-NAME, PROCID, and MSGID.
[src:fluentd/syslog] This does not totally resemble the usage of TAG, but provides the same functionality for most of the cases." Popular syslog tools such as NXLog, Rsyslog conform to this new standard.
[src:fluentd/syslog] The content field should be encoded in a UTF-8 character set and octet values in the traditional ASCII control character range should be avoided.
[src:fluentd/syslog] Generated log messages may be directed to various destinations, including: console, files, remote syslog servers, or relays.
[src:fluentd/syslog] Most implementations provide a command line utility, often called *logger*, as well as a software library, to send messages to the log.
[src:fluentd/syslog] To display and monitor the collected logs, one needs to use a client application or access the log file directly on the system.
[src:fluentd/syslog] The basic command line tools are tail and grep.
[src:fluentd/syslog] The log servers can be configured to send the logs over the network (in addition to the local files).
[src:fluentd/syslog] Some implementations include reporting programs for filtering and displaying syslog messages.
[src:fluentd/syslog] When operating over a network, syslog uses a client-server architecture where the server listens on a well-known or registered port for protocol requests from clients.
[src:fluentd/syslog] Historically the most common transport layer protocol for network logging has been User Datagram Protocol (UDP), with the server listening on port 514.
[src:fluentd/syslog] Because UDP lacks congestion control mechanisms, Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 6514 is used; Transport Layer Security is also required in implementations and recommended for general use.
[src:fluentd/syslog] Since each process, application, and operating system was written independently, there is little uniformity to the payload of the log message.
[src:fluentd/syslog] For this reason, no assumption is made about its formatting or contents.
[src:fluentd/syslog] A syslog message is formatted (RFC 5424 gives the Augmented Backus–Naur form (ABNF) definition), but its MSG field is not.
[src:fluentd/syslog] The network protocol is simplex communication, with no means of acknowledging the delivery to the originator.
[src:fluentd/syslog] Various groups are working on draft standards detailing the use of syslog for more than just network and security event logging, such as its proposed application within the healthcare environment.
[src:fluentd/syslog] Regulations, such as the Sarbanes–Oxley Act, PCI DSS, HIPAA, and many others, require organizations to implement comprehensive security measures, which often include collecting and analyzing logs from many different sources.
[src:fluentd/syslog] The syslog format has proven effective in consolidating logs, as there are many open-source and proprietary tools for reporting and analysis of these logs.
[src:fluentd/syslog] Utilities exist for conversion from Windows Event Log and other log formats to syslog.
[src:fluentd/syslog] Managed Security Service Providers attempt to apply analytical techniques and artificial intelligence algorithms to detect patterns and alert customers to problems.
[src:fluentd/syslog] The Syslog protocol is defined by Request for Comments (RFC) documents published by the Internet Engineering Task Force (Internet standards).
